1933. Mr. Spenoer\nwas appointed as vice-president In\n1918.\nMr. Adams\nPrevious to his association with\nthe Colonial Trust Co., Mr. Adams\nserved as president of ths Nauga\ntuck National Bank from 1939. In\n1999 he was elected ohalrman of\n(Continued on Page 7)\nAssassinate\nChinese\nCommunist\nU Hwo-Shih\nShot Riding\nIn Automobile\nChungking, Oct. I (UP) 14\nHmo-Shih, promt \u00bbmt Chinese Com\nmunistic lead.r, wu assassinated\niMt night while riding through the\n\u2022treote of Chungking in en automo\nbile.\nOommunlet eourcee Mid the as\nsemination might hove been engine\nered by reactionary Kuomlngtang\nelementa in en ettempte to Mbotage\nXuomintang-Oommunlst peace\nLi. M-year-old aecretary of Chung\nking headquarter* of the Communlat\n18th group army and aaaociate edi\ntor of the Communlat newapaper\nBain Rua Jlh Pao, was ahot while\nreturning home from vialtlng a\nfriend at Nankal University.\nLi's chauffeur took him to Chung\nking municipal hoapital, then dis\nappeared. Li died an hour and 17\nminutes later.\nCommunist sources, suggesting it\nmight have been a ease of mistaken\nIdentity, said Li eiosely resembled\nChow En-Lal, one of the leading\nCommunist negotiators in the cur\nrent talks with the gulls/; Kuomin\ntang party.\nLi wm riding in the car in which\nChow often traveled to Nankal Uni\nversity, the newspaper Mid.\nCommunist sources Mid Li had\nno known personal enemies. He was\njailed once for Communist activity,\nbut wm released shortly before the\noutbreak of the Ohlnese-Japanese\nwar.\nlint Since 19S7\nThe assassination wm the first\nof a prominent Communist since\niuontinued on rage 1)\nPrincipals In Changes\nAUSTIN L. ADAMS\nI\nWINTHROP W. SPENCER\nChurthill Challenges\nBritish Labor Party\nNewhouser\nVs. Borowy\nIn Clincher\nBy LEO M. PETERSEN\n(United Press Sport* Editor)\nChloago, Oet. \u2022\u25a0\u2014(UP) Man\n\u2022ter Oharle Orlmm of the Chicago\nCube decided today to gamble with\nan old Detroit Nemeali and named\nHank Borowy to pitch tomorrow In\nthe aeventh game of the world mt\nlei.\nBorowy, who will be ahootlng for\nhie third victory In the poet season\noMteaic, wtU be oppoeed by Hal New*\nhouier, aouthpaw ace of the Tlgeri,\nPordham Hank won 11 and loet\ntwo for the Cabs after they bought\nhim from the New York Yankees in\nmldeeason for I100.0M. If ho U thi\nwinning or losing pitcher he will set\na record. No other pltoher has ever\nfigured in three consecutive series\ndecisions. Le lost the fifth gams\n(Sunday to Newhouser, to 4, and\nreceived credit for Chicago\u2019s to 1\nla-Innlng victory yesterday which\nevened this rlohest series of all time\nat three games each. Borowy had\npitched the opener at Detroit Wed\nnesday, defeating Newhouser to 0,\nSlav Tie Record\nIf he wins tomorrow, he would tie\na record held by several pitchers with\nthree victories In one series.\nHard put for pitching strength,\nOrlmm decided to go with Boroity\nrather than the veteran Paul Der\nringer, who Is the only well-rested\npitcher the Cubs have. He was hop\ning that Borowy once more would\nbe able to continue the Jinx he has\nhold over the Tigers. Before Borowy\nwas sold nut of the American league\nhe had defeated the Tigers 11 times\nwhile losing to them only three. 8o\nthat record, with his world series de\ncisions, means Pordham Hank has\nbeaten the Bengals 13 times while\nlosing to them only four times.\nBorowy was a big gamble, how\never, f6r having pithced both Sunday\nand Monday he will go with only\none day's rest. Normally, a pitcher\nreceives three fufll days' rest be\ntween starting assignments.\nNewhouser, on tip other hand,\nhas been a workhorse for the Tigers\n(Continued on Page 7)\nAxis T rial\nCourt Meets\nBerlin, Oct. i.\u2014(UP)\u2014The four\npower court vhich will hear the\nNuernberg trlale of Axle war crim\ninals met for the first time here to\nday.\nThe meeting In effect comprised\nthe formation of the court, which\nnow was ready to receive Indict\nments of major war criminals. It\nwas described as an Informal ses\nsion of the jurists representing the\nUnited States, Great Britain, Russia\nand Prance.\nThe first indictment, olearlng the\nway for the Nuernberg trials prob\nably next month, was expected to be\nannounced this week.\nl\nAnd particulorly so when the globolly\nfamous American author poses the\nquestion of a woman's share in the\nbargain of marriage. Every man\nevery woman will be interested in\nRupert Hughes' latest story\nBREACH OF PROMISE\nStart it tomorrow night in\nj THE DEMOCRAT\n1 1\nDemands Debate\nOver Failure of\nMinisters Council\nBY W. R. HIGGINBOTHAM\n(United Prw Stef! Correspondent)\nLondon, Oct. 9.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nThe British Labor govern\nment was challenger to a\ngeneral debate on the Foreign\nMinister Council today after\nForeign Secretary Ernest\nBevin disclosed that the con\nference foundered on a sud\nden reversal of Russia\u2019s\nstand on the Balkan peace\ntreaties.\n\"DlMppolBUtf\"\nFormer Prime Minister Winston\nChurchill sroso st the close of Bov\nin's statement and demanded, as\nleader of the Conservative opposi\ntion, thst the government debate\nits handling of tne three-week con\nfemoe.\nChurchill, who previously had In\ndicated he might avoid the issue for\nthe time being to prevent further\ncomplication of a tense interhation\nsi situation, left the timing of the\ndebate to the government.\nBut he branded the results of the\nthree-week foreign ministers' meet\n(Continued on Page 7)\nNew Haven\nMan Gets\nHonor Medal\nWashington, Oct. #\u2014(UP)\u2014Pfc.\nWilliam A. Soderman of West\nHaven, conn., who single-handedly\nknocked out three Oerman tanks\nand routed others with his bazooka\nduring Ardennes campaign, has\nbeen awarded the Congressional\nMedal of Honor, the War Depart\nment announed today.\nHe will receive the decoration\nFriday at the White House.\nWounded\nSoderman assistant gunner was\nwounded in an artillery barrage last\nDec. 16. But he stood his ground\nat Key Road junction leading to\nthe town of Rocherath while his\ncompanions of the 2nd Infantry, In\ndian Head Division fought off the\nGerman onslaught.\nWhen five mark V Panther tanks\ncame in sight, according to Pvt.\nMeredith E. Oliver, Indianapolis,\nInd., Soderman stood up and fired\nhis bazooka, disabling the tank.\nHe remained all night at the in\ntersection under artillery, mortar\nand machinegun fire. Shortly after\ndawn five more Panthers rumbled\ninto view through the fog.\nSoderman knocked the lead tank\nout with a polntblank bazooka shot.\nThe four remr' tanks, unable to\n(Contlr.i on Page 7)\nVichy Leader\nMay Die\nThis Week\nDoomod to Face\nFiring Squad\nFor Trooton\nParis, Oct. 9.\u2014(UP)\u2014\nPierre Laval, France\u2019s arch\ncollaborator with the Nazis\nin World War II, was con\nvicted of treason in the high\ncourt of justice today and\nsentenced to death.\nHour's Deliberation\nThe Jury which heard Laval's\nfive-day trial received the case at\n4:05 p. m. (10:08 a. m. TOT) and\ndeliberated an hour before return\ning its verdict.\nLaval, who refused to attend the\nlast two sessions of his trial, was\nfound guilty on both counts of the\nindlotment plotting against the\nsecurity of the state and intelli\ngence with the enemy.\nThe formor chief of government\nat Vichy was not in the courtroom\nwhen his fate was announced. He\nrebelled against the tumultuous\noourt procedure and sulked in his\noell while his fate wa\u00bb being sealed.\nThe oonvlctlon had not been left\nin doubt since the early sessions of\nhis trial in the paneled oourtroom\nof the Palace of Justice. There\ntwo months ago Marshal Xenrl\nPhilippe Petaln was oonvicted and\nsentenced to death, only to receive\n(Continued on Page 7)\nMore Butter\nScheduled\nFor Civilians\nEighty Million\nSurplus Pound*\nOn Morkot\nWashington, Oct, S-(UP)\u2014eighty\nmillion pounds of butter, declared\nsurplus by the Army, are being turn\ned over to the department of ag\nriculture for disposal to civilian\nagencies, the War Department an\nnounced today.\nThe butter will Increase olvllian\nsupplies greatly during the next few\nmonths during the normal short\nseason in production.\nReleased Seen\nThe butter will be released as soon\nas possible.\nThe Army bought butter for all\nof the armed forces and the war re\nlocation authority. It followed the\npractice of getting its supplies dur\ning the procurement period, needs\n(Continued on Page 7)\nHollywood\nHollywood, Oct. 9-(OP)-Picket*\nend police lined up In front of\nWerner Broe. studios et dewn to\nri ey for the fourth successive dey\nof strike bettles that have already\nsent nearly 70 to hospitals.\nMore than 1,000 pickets of the\nAFL Painters\u2019 Union maintained\nmased lines around the studio yes\nterday. Work continued Inside the\nstudio after 000 nonstrikers stormed\nsix abreast through the gates in a\nriot that Injured scores.\nUnion spokesmen ^aid an even\nstronger picket line would be as\nsembled at 4 a. m. (PST) today, and\na \u2018'cltlens observers committee\u201d\nwould be on hand to witness the\nconduct of all parties.\nAFL\nMany of the nonstrikers, mem\nbers of the AFL International Alli\nance of Stage and Theatrical Em\nployee sought to avoid a repetition\n(Continued on Page 7)\nCongress May Reduce\nCommittees By Fifty\nWashington, Oct. 9\u2014(UP)\u2014The\njoint Senate-House committee to\nreorganize Congress will shortly rec\nommend that both chambers rdeuce\nthe number of their committees by\nmore than 50 per cent, it was\nlearned today.\nThe committee member said that\na formal report will be made to\nCongress within a month. As one\nof its main features, he said, the\nreport probably will advocate the\nconsolidation of the 35 Senate\nlegislative committees Into 13 com\nmittees and the 46 House units\ninto 16.\nSpecial Groap\nThe special 12-member reorgan\niation committ ee was set up last\nyear to study ways and means of\n\u201cstreamlining\" the present legisla\ntive set-up of both houses. With\nSen. Robert M. LaFollette, Jr.,\nFrog.. Wls.. as chairman, the com\nmittee hard tesltmony of more than\n100 congressmen, government ex\nperts and students of political\n1. \u2014An increase in congressional\nsalaries, now $10,000 a year. The\ncommittee probably will favor from\n$15,000 to $20,000. President Truman\nfavors $20,000.\n2. \u2014A retirement system for Con\ngressmen.\n3. \u2014A better staffing of Commit\ntees. Bach committee should have a\nstaff of experts who would be avail\nable at all times for consultation.\n4. \u2014An expansion of the present\nlegislative reference counsel. This\nwould call for maintenance of a\nstaff of legislative experts to help\nthe individual Congressman draw up\nbills and answer his, technical and\nlegal questions.\n5. \u2014The hiring of an \"executive\nassistant\u201d for each representative\nand senator. The assistant would re\nlieve the congressman of the many\nroutine chores that now compete for\nhis time.\nHe said the committee also may\nrecommend a new system of governr\nment for the Diststct of Columbia\n\u201cso that the congress will not have\nLocal Priest In Germany\nLt. (Chaplain) Paul B. Dillon, am of tho late Mr. and Mra. John Dlllra of 1179 Baldwin atroat, la ahown\nabove officiating at an outdoor Maaa for American occupation troop* In Marlburg, Germany. A formor\nmember of the faculty of St. John\u2019* college, Brooklyn, N. Y. Father Dillon la attached to Hoadguartora,\nThird Replacement Unit, and enllatod In tho color* a yoar ago hurt Auguat.\nAmericans Seize Millions\nIn Jap Funds And Loot\nDockers Hiss, Boo\nAs GIs Take-Over\nTruman Will\nHold Secret\nAtomic Code\nTlptonvllle, Tenn., Oct. 9\u2014 (Pres\nWent Truman was firmly determined\ntoday to keep from any other na\ntion of the world, Including all our\nwartime allies, the highly guarded\naecret of how the United States\nmanufactured atomic bombi.\nXe favored, however, wWe Inter\nchange of scientific knowledge re\ngarding atomic energy In the hope\nthat It will load to a new era of\nworWwWe prosperity and peace. The\nPresident relaxed today on restful,\nsprawling Reelfoot lake. Last night,\nsmiling and happy after a big fish\ndinner, he announced:\nStatement\n1. \u2014This country has no Intention\nof sharing with any nation the\nsecret manufacturing processes used\nin atomic bomb production.\n2. \u2014Present unrest between wide\nsegments of labor and management\nin this country was the natural re\nsult of a postwar let-down. He was\nnot worried about It and was con\nfident that with cooperation and\nunderstanding this country would\nmove forward to Its most glorious\nera.\n3. \u2014He was not worried about the\ninternational situation and, on the\nquestion of current difficulties with\nRussia, he cited the long-standing\nfriendship between this country and\nthe Soviet Union, predicting that\nit would continue.\n4. \u2014The President believed this\ncountry and the world face the\ngreatest era In history and cau\ntioned the country not to be\n(Continued on Page 7)\n9-Point Plan\nSet Forth\nBy MAC\nHartford, Conn., Oct. 9 (UP)\nThe Manufacturers Association of\nConnecticut proposed a nine-point\nprogram today which \"should be\nmade effective by Congress and\nother governmental agencies in or\nder to promote conditions conduc\ntive to a quick transition to indus\ntrial peace and a maximum pros\nperity for the American people.\u201d\nThe program emphasized that\ngovernment controls, imposed dur\ning the war, must be removed and\nthat the worker must be given an\n(Continued on Page 7)\nToday's Index\nPage\nAmusements 11\nDr. Brady S\nBob Hope 3\nClassified 13\nComics 13\nCunningham\nCrossword 13\nPage\n?ilm Schedule 11\nMagazine S\nObituaries 3\nDan Parker 10\nPearson\nSoldiers Called in\nTo Unload Troop\nShipi at N. Y.\nNew York, Oct, 9.\u2014(UP)\n\u2014The Army moved In troops\ntoday to unload the Queen\nElizabeth after longshore\nmen refused to work on the\nf'iant troop and cargo-carry\nng British liner.\nFtmm Shipping\nThe longshoremen? action fol\nlowed ahortly after export freight\n\u2022hlpmenta Into New York were froa\nen ait strike of dock workers tied\nup ahipplng In New York harbor.\nSome of the striking stevedores\nhad continued to work on troop\ncarrying ships.\nAbout 13S men In six gangs walked\nout, however, In protest against the\nslae of sling loads used In unloading\nthe ship.\nTwo platoons of the 833rd Labor\nBattalion from the Brooklyn Army\n(Continued on Page 7)\nGovernment\nOf Greece\nResigns\nAthens, Oct. 8\u2014(UP)\u2014The gov\nernment of Premier Petros Voulgar\nls resigned today after the SIAM\nprotested against its decision to hold\nelections In Greece.\nLeaders of the Leftist EAM re\nvealed they had cabled a protest\nagainst the election decision to\nPresident Truman, Prime Minister\nAttlee and Gen. Charles De Gaulle.\nThe Joint message said the EAM\nheld the United States, Britain and\nFrance responsible for the Greek\ngovernment's position on the elec\ntions.\nVoulgaris called on Archbishop\nDamasklnos, regent of Greece, to\ndiscuss the situation. After the con\nference the resignation of the gov\nernment was announced.\nAthens newspapers published a\nreport that 500 American troops were\nexpected to come to Athens from\nItaly to supervise the elections.\nRep. Karl Mundt, R., S. D.. who\nwas In Athens on a Junket, said the\ntroops would be In Greece as ob\nservers and not supervisors of the\nelections.\nPatton's Prosaic\nProscription\nBad Nauheim, Germany.\nOct. (UP)\u2014 Gen. George 8.\nPatton. Jr., who once sought\nmore tanks, ammunition and\ngasoline from the quartermas\nter, today had a new request\u2014\nan \u201ceye-dropper.\u201d\nAssuming command of the\nUnited SUtes 15th Army, a\n\u201cpaper army\u201d which la study\ning American accomplishments\nin Europe, ratten said:\n\u201cI am so engulfed with pa\nperwork that the meet essen\ntial \u00abieee of equipment I need\nis an eye-drepper.\"\nRaid Eitamy\nArsenals for\nAccounting\nTokyo, Oct. 9.\u2014(UP)\u2014\